### (2) Moral of the Story:

The moral of the story is about the dangers of arrogance, self-centeredness, and the pursuit of personal gain without considering the well-being of others. The King of Wei, who was overjoyed at his own success, failed to recognize the potential dangers of his actions. Similarly, the King of Chu, who was overjoyed at his own success, underestimated the importance of humility and the need to consider the actions of others. Both rulers were blinded by their own arrogance and failed to see the broader implications of their decisions. The story serves as a cautionary tale about the dangers of hubris and the importance of humility, self-reflection, and considering the impact of one's actions on others.

